# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web3js
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] An **application binary interface** (**ABI**) is an interface exposed by software that is defined for in-process machine code access.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] Often, the exposing software is a library, and the consumer is a program.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] An ABI is at a relatively low level of abstraction.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] Interface compatibility depends on the target hardware and the software build toolchain.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] In contrast, an application programming interface (API) defines access in source code, which is a relatively high-level, hardware-independent, and human-readable format.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] An API defines an interface at the source code level, before compilation, whereas an ABI defines an interface to compiled code.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] API compatibility is generally the concern for system design and of the toolchain.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] However, a programmer may have to deal with an ABI directly when writing a program in multiple languages or when using multiple compilers for the same language.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] A complete ABI enables a program that supports an ABI to run without modification on multiple operating systems that provide the ABI.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] The target system must provide any required libraries (that implement the ABI), and there may be other prerequisites.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] ABIs include the Intel Binary Compatibility Standard (iBCS) and the System V Release 4 ABIs for various instruction sets.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] An **embedded ABI** (**EABI**), used on an embedded operating system, specifies aspects such as file formats, data types, register usage, stack frame organization, and function parameter passing of an embedded software program.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] Each compiler and assembler that supports an EABI creates object code that is compatible with code generated by other such compilers and assemblers.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] This allows developers to link libraries generated by one compiler with object code generated by another.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] Typically, an EABI is optimized for performance for the limited resources of the target embedded system.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] Therefore, an EABI may omit abstractions between kernel and user space typically found in desktop operating systems.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] The choice of EABI can affect performance.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] Widely used EABIs include the PowerPC, Arm, and MIPS EABIs.
[src:web3js/application-binary-interface] Specific software implementations like the C library may impose additional limitations to form more concrete ABIs; one example is the GNU OABI and EABI for ARM, both of which are subsets of the ARM EABI.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Use the live code editor to try Web3.js in your browser now!
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Keep reading to learn how to use Web3.js in a local development environment.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Note: Installing Web3.js in this way will bring in all Web3.js sub-packages.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Web3.js v4 supports both CommonJS (CJS) and native ECMAScript module (ESM) imports.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Providers are services that are responsible for enabling connectivity with the Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] The `Web3` object must be initialized with a valid provider to function as intended.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Web3.js supports HTTP, WebSocket, and IPC providers, and exposes packages for working with each type of provider.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Web3.js is in compliance with EIP-1193, the Ethereum Provider JavaScript API, so any EIP-1193 provider can be used to initialize the `Web3` object.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] To send transactions to the Ethereum network (e.g. transferring ETH or interacting with smart contracts), it's necessary to use an account with funds to cover gas fees.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] The `Wallet` object is designed to manage a set of accounts that can be used to send transactions with `web3.eth.sendTransaction` or `web3.eth.contract.methods.contractfunction().send()`.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Using the `Wallet` to create a random account is a good way to accelerate the development process, but it's not suitable for mainnet or production uses, since random accounts will not have funds to cover gas fees.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Use the `Wallet.create` method to create a random account.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Use the `Wallet.add` method to use a private key to add an existing account to a wallet.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Private keys are sensitive data and should be treated as such.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Make sure that private keys are kept private, which includes making sure they are not committed to code repositories.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Smart contracts are programs that run on the Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Keep reading to learn how to use Web3.js to interact with smart contracts.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] The first step to interacting with a smart contract is to instantiate it, which requires the ABI and address of the smart contract.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Since reading data from a smart contract does not consume any gas, it's not necessary to use an account to do so.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Writing data to a smart contract consumes gas and requires the use of an account with funds.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Smart contracts emit events to communicate important interactions.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] You can only query logs from the most recent 100,000 blocks.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Web3.js allows user to subscribe to events for real-time notification of important contract interactions.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] HTTP providers do not support real-time event subscriptions.
[src:web3js/getting-started-quickstart] Use one of the other provider types to subscribe to real-time events.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] The concept of an account is central to Ethereum and it can be used to refer to two types of entities that are native to Ethereum: externally-owned accounts and contract accounts.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] This document relates *exclusively* to **externally-owned accounts**.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] An externally-owned account is associated with a "key pair", which is a general concept that is related to public-key cryptography.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] The key pair consists of a private key, which must always be kept secret, and a public key, which is used to derive a public identifier (address) for an account.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] Ethereum accounts have an ETH balance, which can be transferred to other accounts or used to pay for interactions with smart contracts.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] Anyone with access to an account's private key has the ability to control that account's ETH balance, so it's important that an account's private key is always kept secret.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] In addition to the general guidelines for protecting private keys, private keys should never be included in client-side code that can be seen by end users and should never be committed to code repositories.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] In the context of this document, the term "wallet" refers to a collection of accounts and should not be confused with wallet "applications".
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] The `web3-eth-accounts` package contains functions to generate Ethereum accounts, sign transactions and data, and more.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] In Web3.js, the `Web3Account` interface is used to represent an externally-owned account.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] Note that many of these values will change each time the code is executed, since a new account is created each time.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] A Web3.js wallet is a collection of accounts and is represented with the `Wallet` class.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] When a wallet is used to track an account, that account is added to an internal context (i.e.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] `Web3Context`), which makes it easier to use that account in the future - this is described in more detail in the transactions tutorial.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] Note that many of these values will change each time the code is executed, since new accounts are created each time.
[src:web3js/guides-wallet] This document is just an introduction to Web3.js accounts and wallets.
[src:web3js/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:web3js/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:web3js/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:web3js/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:web3js/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:web3js/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:web3js/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:web3js/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:web3js/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:web3js/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:web3js/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:web3js/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:web3js/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:web3js/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:web3js/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:web3js/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:web3js/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:web3js/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:web3js/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:web3js/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:web3js/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:web3js/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:web3js/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:web3js/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:web3js/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:web3js/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:web3js/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:web3js/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:web3js/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:web3js/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:web3js/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:web3js/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:web3js/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:web3js/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:web3js/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:web3js/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:web3js/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:web3js/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:web3js/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:web3js/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:web3js/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:web3js/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:web3js/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:web3js/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:web3js/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:web3js/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:web3js/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:web3js/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:web3js/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:web3js/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:web3js/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:web3js/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:web3js/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:web3js/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:web3js/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:web3js/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:web3js/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:web3js/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:web3js/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:web3js/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:web3js/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:web3js/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:web3js/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:web3js/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:web3js/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:web3js/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:web3js/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:web3js/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:web3js/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:web3js/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:web3js/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:web3js/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:web3js/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:web3js/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:web3js/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:web3js/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:web3js/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:web3js/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:web3js/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:web3js/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:web3js/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:web3js/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:web3js/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:web3js/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:web3js/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:web3js/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:web3js/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:web3js/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:web3js/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:web3js/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:web3js/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:web3js/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:web3js/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:web3js/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:web3js/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:web3js/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:web3js/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:web3js/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:web3js/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:web3js/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:web3js/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:web3js/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:web3js/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:web3js/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:web3js/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:web3js/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:web3js/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:web3js/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:web3js/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:web3js/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:web3js/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:web3js/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:web3js/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:web3js/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:web3js/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:web3js/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:web3js/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:web3js/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:web3js/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:web3js/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:web3js/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:web3js/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:web3js/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:web3js/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:web3js/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:web3js/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:web3js/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:web3js/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:web3js/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:web3js/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:web3js/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:web3js/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:web3js/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:web3js/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:web3js/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:web3js/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:web3js/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:web3js/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:web3js/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:web3js/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:web3js/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:web3js/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:web3js/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:web3js/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:web3js/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:web3js/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:web3js/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:web3js/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:web3js/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:web3js/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:web3js/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:web3js/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:web3js/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:web3js/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:web3js/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:web3js/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:web3js/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:web3js/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:web3js/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:web3js/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:web3js/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:web3js/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:web3js/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:web3js/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:web3js/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:web3js/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:web3js/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:web3js/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:web3js/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:web3js/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:web3js/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:web3js/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:web3js/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:web3js/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:web3js/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:web3js/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:web3js/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:web3js/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:web3js/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:web3js/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:web3js/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:web3js/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:web3js/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:web3js/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:web3js/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:web3js/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:web3js/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:web3js/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:web3js/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:web3js/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:web3js/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:web3js/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:web3js/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:web3js/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:web3js/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:web3js/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:web3js/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:web3js/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:web3js/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:web3js/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:web3js/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:web3js/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:web3js/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:web3js/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:web3js/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:web3js/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:web3js/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:web3js/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:web3js/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:web3js/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:web3js/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] In this tutorial, we will walk through the process of deploying a smart contract to a development network, generating the smart contract's ABI and bytecode, and interacting with the smart contract using Web3.js.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] We will cover the basic concepts of Ethereum, the Solidity smart contract programming language, the Hardhat development environment, and Web3.js.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] If you encounter any issues while following this guide or have any questions, don't hesitate to seek assistance.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Our friendly community is ready to help you out!
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Join our Discord server and head to the **#web3js-general** channel to connect with other developers and get the support you need.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] This tutorial assumes basic familiarity with the command line as well as familiarity with JavaScript and Node.js.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Before starting this tutorial, ensure that Node.js and its package manager, npm, are installed.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] This will create a new `package.json` file in your project directory.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] In this step, we will write the Solidity code for the smart contract and save it as a file in our project directory.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] This simple smart contract defines a `myNumber` variable that can be set by calling the `setMyNumber` function.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] In this step, we will use the Solidity compiler (`solc`) to compile the contract's Solidity code and output the bytecode and ABI that was generated by the Solidity compiler.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] First, install the `solc` package using npm.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Make sure that the version of `solc` is compatible with the version of Solidity that is specified in the smart contract with the `pragma solidity` directive.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] This code reads the Solidity code from the `MyContract.sol` file, compiles it using `solc`, and generates the ABI and bytecode for the smart contract.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] It then writes the bytecode to a new file called `MyContractBytecode.bin` and the contract ABI to `MyContractAbi.json` (these values are also logged to the console).
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] If everything is working correctly, you should see the contract's bytecode and ABI logged to the console and see two new files (`MyContractAbi.json` and `MyContractBytecode.bin`) in the project directory.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Alternatively, you can generate the bytecode and ABI with `npm i solc && npx solcjs MyContract.sol --bin --abi`.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Keep in mind that this will generate files with different names than those used in this tutorial, so the files would need to be renamed to `MyContractBytecode.bin` and `MyContractAbi.json` to follow the rest of this guide exactly as it's written.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Learn more about `solc-js` at https://github.com/ethereum/solc-js.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] In this step, we will set up Web3.js and Hardhat.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Initializing the Hardhat project will require responding to several prompts - select the default option for each prompt.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] After you initialize the Hardhat project, a number of new files and directories will be created.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] The Hardhat development network needs to remain running in the terminal that was used to start it.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Open a new terminal instance in the project directory to execute the remaining commands in this tutorial.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] This code sets up a Web3.js connection to the Hardhat development network and logs the chain ID to the console.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] This tutorial uses the default URL for the Hardhat development network (http://127.0.0.1:8545/).
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Make sure to use the actual URL that was provided when the Hardhat development network was started.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] In this step, we will use Web3.js to deploy the smart contract to the development network.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] This code reads the bytecode from the `MyContractBytecode.bin` file and the ABI from the `MyContractAbi.json` file and uses these values to instantiate a new contract object.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] This example also includes the optional step of estimating the gas that will be used to deploy the smart contract.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] It then deploys the contract to the development network.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Finally, it saves the address of the deployed contract in the `MyContractAddress.txt` file, which will be used when interacting with the contract.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] In this step, we will use Web3.js to interact with the smart contract on the development network.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] This code uses the previously generated ABI and contract address to instantiate a `Contract` object for interacting with the `MyContract` smart contract.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] It gets the current value of `myNumber` from `MyContract`, logs it, updates it, and gets its updated value.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] It logs the updated `myNumber` value and the transaction hash to the console.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] For the purposes of this tutorial, the above script uses relatively arbitrary values for `gas` and `gasPrice` when demonstrating how to interact with a smart contract.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Refer to the Gas and Priority Fees guide to learn how to properly set these values.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] If everything is working correctly, you should see the current counter value logged to the console, followed by the transaction receipt, and then the updated counter value.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] In this tutorial, you learned how to generate the ABI and bytecode of a smart contract, deploy it to a Hardhat development network, and interact with it using Web3.js.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] With this knowledge, you can start experimenting with writing smart contract in order to build decentralized applications (dApps) on the Ethereum network using Web3.js.
[src:web3js/smart-contracts-guide] Keep in mind that this is just the beginning, and there is a lot more to learn about Ethereum and Web3.js - so keep exploring and building, and have fun!
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The createAccessList method is used to create an access list.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Creating an access list in Ethereum is typically associated with Ethereum Improvement Proposal (EIP)-2930, which introduces a way to specify which accounts and storage keys a transaction expects to access.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Access lists are used to optimize gas costs for transactions by providing explicit information about what the transaction needs to access.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The estimateGas function is used to estimate the amount of gas that will be consumed when executing a specific transaction or invoking a contract function.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] This can be very useful when you want to determine the potential cost of a transaction or function call before actually sending it to the Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] It helps users ensure that they have enough ether to cover the gas costs for the operation.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getBalance function is used to retrieve the balance of an Ethereum address, which represents the amount of Ether (ETH) associated with that address.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] It's a fundamental and frequently used function when working with Ethereum applications.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getBlock function is used to retrieve information about a specific Ethereum block.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Ethereum blocks are the fundamental building blocks of the blockchain, containing a collection of transactions and other data.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getBlockNumber function is used to retrieve the latest block number (also known as the block height) of the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The block number is a crucial piece of information in Ethereum as it represents the current state of the blockchain, indicating the total number of blocks that have been mined up to the present.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getBlockTransactionCount function is used to retrieve the number of transactions in a specific Ethereum block.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] It allows you to determine how many transactions were included in a particular block on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getBlockUncleCount function is used to retrieve the number of uncle blocks associated with a specific Ethereum block.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] In Ethereum, uncle blocks (also known as "stale blocks" or "ommer blocks") are blocks that were mined but not included in the main blockchain.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] They are referenced by other blocks as a way to reward miners for their efforts even if their blocks weren't part of the main chain.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getChainId function is used to retrieve the chain ID of the connected Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The chain ID is a unique identifier for a specific Ethereum network, and it's used to help prevent replay attacks when signing transactions.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Different Ethereum networks, such as the mainnet, testnets, and private networks, have distinct chain IDs.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getCode function library is used to retrieve the bytecode of a smart contract deployed on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Smart contracts on Ethereum are typically created by deploying bytecode to a specific address, and this function allows you to fetch the bytecode associated with a particular contract address.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getCoinbase function is used to retrieve the address of the Ethereum account that is currently acting as the coinbase address for mining on the connected Ethereum node.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The coinbase address is the address to which block rewards are sent when miners successfully mine a new block on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Miners configure their coinbase addresses to receive rewards for their mining efforts.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getGasPrice function is used to retrieve the current gas price on the Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Gas price is the amount of Ether (ETH) that users are willing to pay for each unit of gas when executing a transaction on the Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Gas price is an important factor in determining the transaction fee (in ETH) for a transaction.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getPendingTransactions function is used to retrieve information about pending transactions in the Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Pending transactions are transactions that have been submitted to the network but have not yet been included in a mined block.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] This function allows you to access information about transactions that are waiting to be confirmed by miners.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getProof function is used to obtain a Merkle proof or Patricia trie proof for a specific value or data in an Ethereum smart contract's storage.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] This function is typically used when you want to validate that a piece of data is stored in the contract's storage or to provide evidence for data inclusion without having to interact with the entire contract state.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] In Ethereum, storage proofs are used to demonstrate the existence of a value within a contract's storage without querying the entire storage of the contract, which can be computationally expensive.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] These proofs are essential for various applications, including decentralized exchanges, blockchain explorers, and certain cryptographic operations.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] You can use the getProtocolVersion method to retrieve the current Ethereum protocol version of the connected Ethereum node.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getStorageAt method is used to fetch the data stored at a specific storage slot of an Ethereum address.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] It is often used for inspecting the internal state of smart contracts, especially when you want to retrieve the value of a specific variable in a contract's storage.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getTransaction method allows you to retrieve information about a transaction based on its transaction hash.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getTransactionCount method allows you to retrieve the transaction count (nonce) of a specific Ethereum address.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getTransactionReceipt method allows you to retrieve the transaction receipt for a specific transaction based on its transaction hash.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The getUncle method allows you to retrieve information about an uncle block at a specific index within a given block.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The isMining function returns a boolean value, indicating whether the node is actively mining or not.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The isSyncing method allows you to check the current synchronization status of your Ethereum node.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The sendTransaction method is used to create and send a transaction to the Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Please be cautious when sending transactions, especially when dealing with smart contracts, as they may execute specific functions that can have irreversible effects.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Always ensure that the details in your transaction object are accurate and intended.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Here you can find more examples how to send transaction.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The sign method is used to sign a message or data using a private key.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] This is often used to prove ownership or authorship of a specific piece of data or to provide cryptographic proof in various Ethereum-related operations.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The signTransaction method is used to sign an Ethereum transaction, creating a signed transaction object that can be broadcast to the Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] The sendSignedTransaction method is used to send a signed Ethereum transaction to the Ethereum network.
[src:web3js/web3-eth-methods] Before sending a transaction, you need to sign it using a private key, and then you can use this method to broadcast the signed transaction to the network.
[src:web3js/web3] Academic surveys describe Web3 as combining smart contract platforms, peer-to-peer networks, and cryptographic mechanisms, while noting trade-offs involving scalability, interoperability, and governance.
[src:web3js/web3] Critics have expressed concerns over the centralization of wealth to a small group of investors and individuals, or a loss of privacy due to more expansive data collection.
[src:web3js/web3] Billionaires like Elon Musk and Jack Dorsey have argued that web3 only serves as a buzzword or marketing term.
[src:web3js/web3] Web 1.0 and Web 2.0 refer to eras in the history of the World Wide Web as it evolved through various technologies and formats.
[src:web3js/web3] Web 1.0 refers roughly to the period from 1991 to 2004, where most sites consisted of static pages, and the vast majority of users were consumers, not producers of content.
[src:web3js/web3] Web 2.0 is based around the idea of "the web as platform" and centers on user-created content uploaded to forums, social media and networking services, blogs, and wikis, among other services.
[src:web3js/web3] Web 2.0 is generally considered to have begun around 2004 and continues to the current day.
[src:web3js/web3] Web3 is distinct from Tim Berners-Lee's 1999 concept of a Semantic Web, which was also sometimes referred to as Web 3.0.
[src:web3js/web3] While the Semantic Web envisioned a web of linked data, web3 in the blockchain context refers to a decentralized internet built upon distributed ledger technologies.
[src:web3js/web3] Ethereum co-founder Gavin Wood first popularized the use of the term Web 3.0 in a blockchain context in 2014.
[src:web3js/web3] Wood used the term to refer to a "decentralized online ecosystem based on blockchain." "Web3" and "Web 3.0" have been used interchangeably by later writers, leading to confusion between the two concepts.
[src:web3js/web3] In popular and industry usage, "Web 3.0" is sometimes used interchangeably with "web3" to refer to blockchain-based proposals rather than the Semantic Web.
[src:web3js/web3] The definition of the term has been described by *Bloomberg* journalist Olga Kharif as "hazy", but it revolves around the idea of decentralization and often incorporate blockchain technologies, such as various cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:web3js/web3] Kharif has described web3 as an idea that "would build financial assets, in the form of tokens, into the inner workings of almost anything you do online".
[src:web3js/web3] Web3 has been proposed as a possible response to the over-centralization of the web in a few Big Tech companies.
[src:web3js/web3] Web3 could potentially improve data security, scalability, and privacy.
[src:web3js/web3] According Kharif in December 2021, skeptics say the idea "is a long way from proving its use beyond niche applications, many of them tools aimed at crypto traders".
[src:web3js/web3] DuPont et al (2024) describe web3 as an umbrella term for NFTs, cryptocurrency, and blockchain which appeals to users who are "not necessarily plugged into the cypher-punk or crypto-anarchist ideals of Bitcoin".
[src:web3js/web3] Rohn (2025) describes the term as synonymous with "blockchain economy".
[src:web3js/web3] In 2019, *The Conversation* quoted legal scholars discussing concerns over the difficulty of regulating a decentralized web, which they reported might make it more difficult to prevent cybercrime, online harassment, hate speech, and the dissemination of child sexual abuse material.
[src:web3js/web3] The concept of Web3 has also been described as a part of a cryptocurrency bubble, and as an extension of harmful and short-lived blockchain-based trends such as NFTs.
[src:web3js/web3] The use of cryptocurrencies, NFTs, and blockchains in general also introduce potential harmful environmental effects.
[src:web3js/web3] Others have expressed beliefs that web3 and the associated technologies are a pyramid scheme.
[src:web3js/web3] Web3 proposals often include decentralized autonomous organizations (DAOs) and decentralized finance (DeFi).
[src:web3js/web3] Marlinspike also remarked that the new web resembles the old web.
[src:web3js/web3] In 2021, interest in the web3 concept began to increase.
[src:web3js/web3] Particular interest spiked toward the end of 2021, largely due to interest from cryptocurrency enthusiasts and investments from high-profile technologists and companies.
[src:web3js/web3] Executives from venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz traveled to Washington, DC, in October 2021 to lobby for the idea as a potential solution to questions about regulation of the web, with which policymakers have been grappling.
[src:web3js/web3] *The New York Times* and *Fortune* reported in December 2021 that $27 billion had been invested in blockchain projects due to interest in the Web3 concept.
[src:web3js/web3] In late 2021, Reddit, Discord, and other Web 2.0 companies experimented with incorporating web3 technologies into their platforms.
[src:web3js/web3] On November 8, 2021, Discord CEO Jason Citron tweeted a screenshot suggesting the platform might be integrating cryptocurrency wallets into their platform.
[src:web3js/web3] Two days later, and after heavy user backlash, Discord announced they had no plans to integrate such technologies and that it was an internal-only concept that had been developed in a company-wide hackathon.
[src:web3js/web3] It's what parents tell their kids about at night if they want them to grow up to become economists".
[src:web3js/web3] That same month, Jack Dorsey, co-founder and former CEO of Twitter, dismissed web3 as a "venture capitalists' plaything".
[src:web3js/web3] Dorsey opined that web3 will not democratize the internet, but it will shift power from players like Facebook to venture capital funds like Andreessen Horowitz.
